<% content_for :title, "Flat Files Instructions — AACT" %>

<div class="mb-6">
  <%= render "shared/back_link", path: snapshots_path, label: "Snapshots" %>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-2">Pipe-Delimited Flat Files Instructions</h1>
</div>

<div class="max-w-3xl space-y-8">
  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow p-6">
    <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">Overview</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-3">
      Pipe-delimited flat files contain AACT data with fields separated by the
      <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded text-xs">|</code> character. These files are designed for users who
      prefer text-based formats or analysis tools like R, SAS, Python, or SPSS.
    </p>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
      The AACT system provides access to the <strong>30 most recent daily snapshots</strong> along with
      permanent <strong>monthly archives</strong> created on the first day of each month.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow p-6">
    <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">File Format Details</h2>
    <ul class="text-sm text-gray-700 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Delimiter:</strong> Pipe character <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded text-xs">|</code>. Consecutive pipes indicate a null or missing value.</li>
      <li><strong>Encoding:</strong> UTF-8.</li>
      <li><strong>Header row:</strong> First row contains column names matching the AACT database schema.</li>
      <li><strong>One file per table:</strong> e.g. <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded text-xs">studies.txt</code>, <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded text-xs">interventions.txt</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>Embedded pipes:</strong> Fields containing a pipe are enclosed in double quotes to prevent misinterpretation.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow p-6">
    <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-6">Steps</h2>
    <ol class="space-y-6">
      <li class="flex gap-4">
        <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-navy text-white text-sm font-bold rounded-full flex items-center justify-center">1</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-medium text-gray-900 mb-1">Download a snapshot</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
            Get the <%= link_to "latest snapshot", snapshots_path, class: "text-blue hover:underline" %> or
            browse the <%= link_to "archive", archive_snapshots_path(type: "flatfiles"), class: "text-blue hover:underline" %> for older data.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>

      <li class="flex gap-4">
        <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-navy text-white text-sm font-bold rounded-full flex items-center justify-center">2</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-medium text-gray-900 mb-1">Extract the ZIP file</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
            Unzip into a folder of your choice. You'll find a set of <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded text-xs">.txt</code> files named after their corresponding database tables.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>

      <li class="flex gap-4">
        <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-navy text-white text-sm font-bold rounded-full flex items-center justify-center">3</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-medium text-gray-900 mb-1">Open with your analysis tool</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-2">
            Use any tool that supports pipe-delimited files. Popular options:
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm text-gray-700 space-y-1">
            <li><strong>R:</strong> <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded text-xs">read.csv("studies.txt", sep="|")</code></li>
            <li><strong>Python (pandas):</strong> <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded text-xs">pd.read_csv("studies.txt", sep="|")</code></li>
            <li><strong>SAS:</strong> Use INFILE with <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded text-xs">DELIMITER='|'</code></li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-500">
            Note: Excel is not recommended — many files exceed Excel's row limits.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</div>
